’s power is disguised through careful stage management of media representations of the royal family. In so doing, it extends conventional understandings of what monarchy is and why it matters.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEqualityzGreat Britain. 0aMonarchyzGreat Britain. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aBritish monarchy.  aQueen Elizabeth II.  acultural political economy.  aideology.  ainequalities.  amedia representation.  apower.  aroyal family.  asocial class.  athe elites.1 aClancy, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2021 eBook-Packagez978311128198840uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152614934340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526149343423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526149343/original  a978-3-11-128198-8  Manchester University Press 2021 eBook-Packageb2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles